INFLUENZA (07): SPAIN (CANARY ISLANDS)
**************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 2 Feb 2012
Source: La Provincia, Diario de Las Palmas (DLP), Canary Islands, Spain [in Spanish, trans. Mod.JW, edited]
http://www.laprovincia.es/sociedad/2012/02/02/canarias-situacion-epidemica-gripe/435637.html


The Ministry of Health reported yesterday [1 Feb 2012] that in the last week flu cases have doubled over the previous week, with a rate of 198 cases per 100 000 inhabitants, representing an epidemic situation. A note from the department reported that it expects this epidemic to last for the next 3-4 weeks and to register a large number of cases of influenza, which at the moment especially affects children under 5. The Health department said the H3 [presumably the A/(H3N2) current seasonal strain] subtype is the only one that has been isolated from samples from patients, and indicates that this situation is similar to the rest of Spain.

To date 6 cases have been hospitalized with severe flu; 3 are under 5 years old and one of them had a risk factor for complications from influenza, but they are all discharged. The other 3 cases are adults with risk factors who remain hospitalized.

The Health department insists that vaccination is the most effective measure against the influenza and all people with risk factors for complications of influenza (65 and older, chronically ill, obese, pregnant women) should be vaccinated and persons who live with or are taking care of them. It recommends that on the appearance of flu symptoms (sudden onset with cough, fever, and malaise) you should see a health centre and strictly follow the treatment prescribed by your doctor while emergency services, especially hospitals, should be reserved for severe cases and thus avoid unnecessary over-loading, affecting the assistance "of those most in need."

